40|$|Cornelio Fabro {{suggested}} that Kant’s conception of freedom leads to existential atheism and existential amoralism, and these, in their turn, entail theoretical atheism. This essay analyses and supports Fabro’s argument. In particular {{it focuses on}} Fabro’s claim {{that no one can}} be the ruler of oneself, and on his view that, on an existential level, i. e. from the first personal perspective of an agent, only a reference to God can ground <b>a</b> substantial <b>moral</b> <b>obligation.</b> On the ground of the suggested theses, Fabro’s interpretation of Kant seems plausible, and Kant’s unintended {{role in the development of}} modern atheism seems clea...|$|R
